      .mainText
        p Meet PolyBiome, an initiative to reduce the carcinogenic potential of meat using safe microorganisms in our body.
        h1 MEET THE 
          span POLYBIOME 
          | PROJECT
    #sec1.sec
      .textSec
        h2
          span One 
          |in every 33 
          span cancers 
          |is ascribed to processed or red meat. 
        p In an unprecedented 
          span
            a(href='http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/statements/2015/processed-meat-cancer/',target="_blank") statement
          |, the World Health Organization  announced in October 2015 their concern in reference to recent studies by the International Agency for Research on Cancer (IARC) which related processed and red meat intake with colorectal cancer.

      .imgSec
        img(src='img/ribbonOrange.png').img-responsive#ribbon
        img(src='img/omsMeat.png').img-responsive#omsMeat
      .textSec.spacedTop
        p The studies found that 21% of bowel cancers are caused by processed or red meat, which accounts for a 3% of the total world cancers. In the Carcinogenic Groups classification processed meats rank now in the first risk group and red meats in the second.
      .imgSec.spacedBottom
        img(src='img/cow.png').food
        img(src='img/pig.png').food   
        img(src='img/bacon.png').food
        img(src='img/lamb.png',style="max-width: 40%; margin-left:20px").food
    hr
    #sec2.noOverflow.sec
      .textSec
        h2
          span Polyamines 
          | are primarily responsible for the potential carcinogenicity of meat.
        p These small molecules are involved in processes such as cell proliferation and are, in small quantities, essential for our bodies. However, if there is a imbalance in their concentration, for example, due to continuous meat intake, polyamines can upregulate proliferation, increasing cancer risk and becoming harmful for our health.
      .imgSec
        img(src='img/mol1.png').img-responsive#mol1
        img(src='img/mol2.png').img-responsive#mol2
       .textSec.spacedBottom  
        p Once absorbed in the lower intestine, polyamines enter the blood flow and spread across the body, where efficient targeting and control is difficult. Therefore, it is necessary an approach that eliminates them before they are absorbed. 
      .imgSec
        img(src='img/vessel.gif').img-responsive#veins
    hr
    #sec3.sec
      .textSec.spacedBottom
        h2 Polybiome aims to effectively reduce 
          span polyamine levels 
          | by targeting them in the absorbing phase.
        p Polybiome is a probiotic consisting on bacteria which degrade the poliamines in the intestinal tract, reducing the external intake and thus minimizing the risk factor of cancer.
      .imgSec
        img(src='img/shield.gif').img-responsive#shield    
